<h2>The Therapeutic Relationship Is Central — But Not Infallible</h2>
<p>Research consistently identifies the therapeutic alliance — the quality of the working relationship between client and therapist — as one of the strongest predictors of therapy outcomes. Getting that relationship right matters enormously. And sometimes, despite best efforts on both sides, it's not right — or the therapist doesn't have the skills for what you need.</p>

<p>Staying with a therapist who isn't helping is extremely common. People feel guilty, worry about hurting the therapist's feelings, or assume the lack of progress is their own fault. These feelings are understandable and wrong. A good therapist will support your decision to seek someone else if the work isn't progressing.</p>

<h2>Signs It May Be Time to Switch</h2>

<p><strong>No improvement after 8–12 sessions.</strong> Most evidence-based therapies produce meaningful improvement within the first 8–12 sessions. If you're well past this and nothing has shifted, something isn't working — either the approach, the fit, or both.</p>

<p><strong>You don't feel heard or understood.</strong> You leave sessions feeling unseen, misinterpreted, or like the therapist has a framework they're fitting you into rather than genuinely engaging with your experience.</p>

<p><strong>The therapist doesn't have expertise in what you're dealing with.</strong> A generalist therapist seeing someone with OCD, an eating disorder, or complex trauma without specialist training is likely to underdeliver. If your presenting concern requires specialist skills, seek them.</p>

<p><strong>You feel worse consistently.</strong> Early therapy can be difficult — engaging with painful material often involves temporary distress. But a consistent pattern of feeling worse after sessions, with no improvement over time, is a sign to reassess.</p>

<p><strong>Boundary concerns.</strong> Inappropriate self-disclosure, contact outside sessions that crosses professional lines, a therapist who seems to need something from you — these are clear signals to leave.</p>

<p><strong>Your needs have changed.</strong> The therapist you needed for one presenting problem may not be the right person for a new or different concern. Needs evolve; it's legitimate to seek someone whose skillset matches your current situation.</p>

<h2>What Might Not Be a Reason to Switch</h2>

<p><strong>Discomfort.</strong> Therapy is often uncomfortable. Engaging with avoided material, hearing feedback about patterns, doing difficult work — this is part of the process. Discomfort alone isn't a signal to leave; it may be a signal that important work is happening.</p>

<p><strong>Not liking something you heard.</strong> A good therapist will sometimes say things that are challenging or that you initially resist. "I didn't like what they said" is worth sitting with before using it as a reason to leave.</p>

<p><strong>A difficult patch.</strong> Therapy fluctuates. A few difficult sessions are not the same as a therapeutic relationship that isn't working.</p>

<h2>How to Make the Transition</h2>
<p>If you decide to switch, you don't need to have a confrontational conversation with your current therapist. You can simply let them know you're ending. If you feel able, a brief conversation about why can be useful — both for your own clarity and because therapists benefit from feedback. You're not obligated to justify your decision.</p>

<p>Your notes and records belong to you. You can request them for a new therapist.</p>

<h2>Frequently Asked Questions</h2>

<p><strong>Will I have to start over completely?</strong><br/>
Some context-building is inevitable with a new therapist, but much of what you've learned and processed transfers. Many people find that a second therapist builds on earlier work rather than starting from zero.</p>

<p><strong>Is it okay to see two therapists at once?</strong><br/>
Generally not recommended without coordination. Two therapists with different approaches can work at cross-purposes. If you're specifically seeking a second opinion on approach, a one-off consultation is better than parallel ongoing work.</p>

